{
  "doc_id": "3489",
  "text": "Huntingtin Yeast-two hybrid Protein K (HYPK) is a huntingtin-interacting protein that has been shown to reduce aggregation and apoptosis in a Huntington's disease (HD) model [CITATION_1] . HYPK is shown to have chaperone-like properties [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] and is present in a ribosome associated chaperone complex with MPP11 [CITATION_4] . Our previous study showed that HYPK is an intrinsically unstructured protein (IUP) with a pre-molten globule like conformation [CITATION_5] . However, under physiological conditions, HYPK is predicted to have ~36.7% secondary structure [CITATION_6] . HYPK undergoes a conformational change from a pre-molten globule to a molten globule form, by a calcium-dependent mechanism [CITATION_7] .",
